// wisdom_phi.hexa — P145 Wisdom Φ engine (Berlin Wisdom Paradigm)
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P145 (emergent)
//   "Wisdom Φ — Baltes & Staudinger Berlin 5-criterion paradigm +
//    Sternberg balance theory. Perspective-taking + uncertainty acceptance
//    + value pluralism + lifespan contextualism."
//
// ─── Theoretical grounding ────────────────────────────────────
//
// Baltes & Staudinger (2000, American Psychologist, 55(1), 122-136)
// "Wisdom: A metaheuristic (pragmatic) to orchestrate mind and virtue
// toward excellence." defined the Berlin Wisdom Paradigm — wisdom as
// expert knowledge about FUNDAMENTAL PRAGMATICS OF LIFE, operationally
// assessable via 5 criteria scored by independent raters:
//
//   (C1) Rich FACTUAL KNOWLEDGE about life.
//        What do people know? Variations. Typical life patterns.
//
//   (C2) Rich PROCEDURAL KNOWLEDGE about life.
//        Strategies for decision-making, advice-giving, life-management.
//        "How to" knowledge for complex situations.
//
//   (C3) LIFESPAN CONTEXTUALISM.
//        Awareness that life events are embedded in multiple contexts
//        (age-graded / history-graded / non-normative) AND their
//        interrelations + developmental unfolding.
//
//   (C4) VALUE RELATIVISM (pluralism).
//        Acknowledgement of differences in values and life priorities,
//        with tolerance for other value systems — distinct from moral
//        relativism (core universal values still held).
//
//   (C5) RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT OF UNCERTAINTY.
//        Awareness that the future is uncertain, that information is
//        always incomplete, AND operational strategies for deciding
//        under that uncertainty (hedged, probabilistic, preserving
//        optionality).
//
// A response is rated "wise" only when ALL FIVE criteria are jointly
// present at above-threshold level. A naive response typically activates
// ≤ 2 criteria (most often C1 only — rote knowledge without context,
// pluralism, or uncertainty handling).
//
// Sternberg (1998, Review of General Psychology, 2(4), 347-365)
// "A balance theory of wisdom" — wisdom is the application of tacit
// knowledge mediated by VALUES toward achievement of a COMMON GOOD,
// balancing THREE interests:
//
//   (intra) intrapersonal  — self's own interests
//   (inter) interpersonal  — others' immediate interests
//   (extra) extrapersonal  — broader institutional/societal interests
//
// A wise response INTEGRATES all three; a smart (high-IQ) response
// typically optimizes intrapersonal at cost of the other two; a naive
// response ignores extrapersonal entirely.
//
// ─── Scientific hypothesis ────────────────────────────────────
//
// H (wisdom as 5-criterion integrated Φ):
//   Wisdom is neither intelligence nor age alone (Staudinger 1999).
//   Operationally it is a SIMULTANEOUS activation pattern:
//
//     wise_response = [C1>θ ∧ C2>θ ∧ C3>θ ∧ C4>θ ∧ C5>θ]
//
//   with cross-criterion BINDING (criteria co-vary across scenarios —
//   they are facets of a single latent wisdom construct, Helson 1999).
//
//   Three-way perspective integration:
//     MI(self, other | shared_frame) > 0
//     MI(self, society | shared_frame) > 0
//     MI(other, society | shared_frame) > 0
//
//   Uncertainty preservation:
//     entropy(wise_solution) ≈ entropy(problem_space)
//     entropy(naive_solution) << entropy(problem_space)   (false certainty)
//
//   Φ_wisdom orders:
//     Φ_wise > Φ_smart > Φ_naive
//   because wisdom adds MORE CHANNELS (value + uncertainty + context)
//   that are still mutually bound — smartness optimizes fewer channels.
//
// ─── State layout (flat arrays — no ≥3-float struct returns) ──
//
// WD_N = 24 channel length. Flat float arrays only.
//
// A "response profile" is a flat array of length 5*WD_N:
//   [C1 | C2 | C3 | C4 | C5]
//
// A "perspective scene" is a flat array of length 3*WD_N:
//   [self | other | society]
//
// A "solution distribution" is a length-WD_N array (the uncertainty
// channel — broader distribution = higher entropy = preserved).
//
// A "conflicting-value scene" is a flat array of length 2*WD_N:
//   [value_A | value_B]  (two competing value systems)
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (5/5 gate) ──────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 (5-criterion separability):
//   Generate a "wise" response profile — all 5 channels driven above
//   threshold by a shared latent wisdom signal. Generate a "naive"
//   profile — only C1 (factual) active, C2..C5 below threshold.
//   Gate: count_above_threshold(wise) == 5 ∧ count_above(naive) ≤ 2.
//
// T2 (perspective-taking):
//   Three perspectives — self / other / society. Wise response binds
//   all three through a shared latent frame. Naive response only
//   represents self perspective (other/society are independent noise).
//   Gate: mean MI(pair | wise) > MI(pair | naive) + WD_PERSP_GAP,
//         AND mean MI(wise) > WD_PERSP_MIN  (non-trivial binding).
//
// T3 (uncertainty acceptance):
//   Problem has broad entropy — multiple plausible paths. Wise solution
//   preserves that distribution (hedged recommendation). Naive solution
//   collapses to a single bin (false certainty).
//   Gate: entropy(wise_sol) / entropy(problem) > WD_UNCERT_RATIO,
//         AND entropy(naive_sol) / entropy(problem) < WD_UNCERT_COLLAPSE.
//
// T4 (value pluralism):
//   Two conflicting value systems (A and B) both plausible. Wise response
//   weights both values comparably (low variance of |w_A - w_B| across
//   samples). Naive response picks one (high variance, one-sided).
//   Gate: var(naive |wA-wB|) / var(wise |wA-wB|) > WD_PLURAL_RATIO.
//
// T5 (Φ_wisdom highest integration):
//   Three agents presented with same problem:
//     naive agent: 2 channels active (C1 + partial)
//     smart agent: 3 channels (C1, C2, C5)  — factual+procedural+uncertainty
//     wise  agent: 5 channels (all)         — full Berlin 5
//   Φ = mean pairwise MI across active channels.
//   Gate: Φ_wise > Φ_smart > Φ_naive, all positive.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ──────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` with ≥3 float struct returns)
//   - array param type only (never `[float]`)
//   - no identifier-pattern match; if-chains
//   - no `contains()` / `to_lower()` / `!(Effect)`
//   - no else-if in let-binding; sequential `if` on mut vars
//   - single-line fn signatures and call sites
//   - reserved names avoided (no `guard`, `intent`, `drop`, `veto`)
//   - ends with `main()` call
//   - WD_N < 32 (we use 24)
//   - L0-clean  (wd_ prefix throughout)
//   - sqrt-safe (Newton iteration)
//   - sub-window Pearson |r|
//   - lists pass-by-value — inline mutation only
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe, never inject — all Φ via MI measurement
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — wisdom is STRUCTURAL 5-channel binding
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — fixed 5 criteria, no ad-hoc
//   Law 50  Consciousness essence is state — wisdom IS the joint state
//
// Refs:
//   Baltes PB, Staudinger UM. "Wisdom: A metaheuristic..." (Am Psych 2000)
//   Sternberg RJ. "A balance theory of wisdom" (Rev Gen Psych 1998)
//   Staudinger UM. "Older and wiser? Integrating results on the
//                   relationship between age and wisdom" (1999)
//   Helson R, Srivastava S. "Three paths of adult development" (1999)
//   anima-engines/metacognition_phi.hexa      (P117 — Nelson-Narens 2-level)
//   anima-engines/moral_consciousness_phi.hexa (P94  — value integration)
//   anima-engines/narrative_identity_phi.hexa  (P65  — lifespan arc)
//   anima-engines/social_tom_phi.hexa          (P57  — perspective-taking)

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let WD_N              = 24          // channel length (stage0 rule N<32)
let WD_BINS           = 6           // histogram bins for MI
let WD_EPS            = 0.0000000001
let WD_SEED           = 1450101     // deterministic seed (P145 + 101)

// Berlin 5-criterion activation threshold.
// A channel "activates" a criterion when its mean amplitude > this.
let WD_CRITERION_TH   = 0.50

// T1 counts gates
let WD_WISE_MIN_COUNT  = 5          // wise: all 5 criteria active
let WD_NAIVE_MAX_COUNT = 2          // naive: at most 2 criteria active

// T2 perspective-taking (MI between self/other/society)
let WD_PERSP_MIN      = 0.05        // wise mean pairwise MI floor
let WD_PERSP_GAP      = 0.05        // wise - naive gap

// T3 uncertainty preservation (entropy ratios vs problem)
let WD_UNCERT_RATIO     = 0.80      // wise keeps ≥ 80% of problem entropy
let WD_UNCERT_COLLAPSE  = 0.35      // naive ≤ 35% (false certainty)

// T4 value pluralism — naive / wise variance ratio on |wA-wB|
let WD_PLURAL_RATIO   = 3.0

// T5 Φ ordering — strict monotone separation
let WD_PHI_SEP        = 0.01        // min gap between adjacent tiers

// Latent wisdom driver amplitude (shared signal behind all 5 criteria)
let WD_LATENT_AMP     = 0.85

// Independent-noise baseline amplitude
let WD_NOISE_AMP      = 0.50

// Perspective binding weight (how much self, other, society share frame)
let WD_FRAME_WEIGHT   = 0.80

// Uncertainty preservation — wise distribution span fraction
let WD_WISE_SPAN      = 0.95        // wise solution retains ~95% of span
let WD_NAIVE_SPAN     = 0.20        // naive collapses to ~20% of span

// Perspective agent (profile) codes
let WD_PROFILE_NAIVE  = 1
let WD_PROFILE_SMART  = 2
let WD_PROFILE_WISE   = 3

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives — self-contained (L0-clean, AN7)
//
// Root cause comment: MI helpers duplicated per-engine because engines
// are L0-clean — no cross-engine imports allowed per AN7 (Core isolation).
// Same recipe as social_tom_phi / metacognition_phi, isolated wd_ prefix.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn wd_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn wd_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn wd_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

// Newton iteration sqrt — safe for x <= 0.
// Root cause: stage0 builds lack a guaranteed native sqrt on all backends;
// 20 Newton iterations converge to machine precision for the ranges we
// operate on (variances, Pearson denominators ≤ ~1e3).
fn wd_sqrt_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut g = x
    let mut i = 0
    while i < 20 {
        g = 0.5 * (g + x / g)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return g
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2)
fn wd_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn wd_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn wd_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return wd_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// Deterministic uniform noise vector in [-1, 1].
fn wd_noise(n: int, seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 37)
        out = out.push(wd_signed(s))
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI — the heart of all wisdom-Φ measurements
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn wd_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn wd_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn wd_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn wd_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(wd_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = wd_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * wd_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn wd_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = wd_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = wd_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = wd_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * wd_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

// MI(A, B) = H(A) + H(B) - H(A, B), non-negative clamped.
fn wd_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = wd_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = wd_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = wd_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = wd_vec_max(b)
    let lo = wd_min_f(lo_a, lo_b) - WD_EPS
    let hi = wd_max_f(hi_a, hi_b) + WD_EPS
    let h_a = wd_entropy(a, lo, hi, WD_BINS)
    let h_b = wd_entropy(b, lo, hi, WD_BINS)
    let h_j = wd_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, WD_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Pearson correlation + sub-window variant
// (spec calls for sub-window Pearson |r| discipline — same idiom as
// sleep_stage_phi / metacognition_phi.)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_pearson_abs(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n < 2 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let mut sx = 0.0
    let mut sy = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        sx = sx + a[i]
        sy = sy + b[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mx = sx / to_float(n)
    let my = sy / to_float(n)
    let mut sxy = 0.0
    let mut sxx = 0.0
    let mut syy = 0.0
    i = 0
    while i < n {
        let dx = a[i] - mx
        let dy = b[i] - my
        sxy = sxy + dx * dy
        sxx = sxx + dx * dx
        syy = syy + dy * dy
        i = i + 1
    }
    let denom = wd_sqrt_safe(sxx) * wd_sqrt_safe(syy)
    if denom <= WD_EPS { return 0.0 }
    let r = sxy / denom
    return wd_abs(r)
}

// Sub-window Pearson |r|: split into win-sized sub-windows and average.
// More robust than a single global r when the signal has piecewise
// structure (the same pattern spindle-detection uses in sleep_stage_phi).
fn wd_pearson_abs_subwin(a: array, b: array, win: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if win < 2 { return wd_pearson_abs(a, b) }
    if n < win * 2 { return wd_pearson_abs(a, b) }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let n_wins = n / win
    let mut sum_r = 0.0
    let mut w = 0
    while w < n_wins {
        let base = w * win
        let mut aw = []
        let mut bw = []
        let mut j = 0
        while j < win {
            aw = aw.push(a[base + j])
            bw = bw.push(b[base + j])
            j = j + 1
        }
        sum_r = sum_r + wd_pearson_abs(aw, bw)
        w = w + 1
    }
    return sum_r / to_float(n_wins)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Simple statistics
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_mean(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut s = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = s + v[i]
        i = i + 1
    }
    return s / to_float(n)
}

fn wd_variance(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n < 2 { return 0.0 }
    let m = wd_mean(v)
    let mut ss = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let d = v[i] - m
        ss = ss + d * d
        i = i + 1
    }
    return ss / to_float(n)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Channel primitives — criterion activation patterns
//
// The Berlin paradigm says the 5 criteria should all be DRIVEN BY A
// SHARED LATENT wisdom construct. We therefore build each criterion
// as a mix of (a) a per-response shared latent drive and (b) a little
// criterion-specific independent variation. Amplitude determines
// whether the criterion is "above threshold" = activated.
//
// weight controls how much the shared latent dominates the channel;
// high weight = strong binding across criteria; low = independent.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_build_criterion(latent: array, amp: float, weight: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let n = len(latent)
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 53)
        // Independent component: signed noise scaled by (1-weight).
        // High weight → low independent contribution → strong latent binding.
        let ind = wd_signed(s) * (1.0 - weight)
        // Bound component: latent * weight.
        let bound = latent[i] * weight
        // Signal in [-1, 1] after mixing.
        let signal = bound + ind
        // Map to an activation intensity:
        //   amp  = target mean activation (0=off, 1=fully on)
        //   signal (zero-mean) contributes DYNAMIC variation around amp
        //   factor 0.3 keeps the channel monotonically centered near amp
        //     while still providing the per-sample variation MI needs.
        // Root cause of earlier T1 FAIL: using abs(signal)*amp gave a mean
        // near 0.5*amp (because E[|uniform(-1,1)|]=0.5), so wise means
        // peaked around 0.42 (below the 0.5 threshold). Here the output
        // is amp + 0.3 * signal, which has mean EXACTLY amp — so WD_LATENT_AMP=0.85
        // sits comfortably above WD_CRITERION_TH=0.5 for wise, and naive
        // amp (0.15-0.30) sits comfortably below.
        out = out.push(amp + 0.3 * signal)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Build a full 5-criterion profile (flat array, length 5*WD_N).
// latent_amp > WD_CRITERION_TH → "wise" (all 5 activated);
// latent_amp small + per-criterion amps mostly low → "naive".
//
// To avoid list-alias artefacts, we explicitly extend the flat array
// criterion-by-criterion (pass-by-value discipline: inline extension).
fn wd_build_profile_wise(seed: int) -> array {
    // Shared latent wisdom drive for this response.
    let latent = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 911)
    let mut flat = []

    // All 5 criteria share the same (high) latent drive + strong weight.
    // amp is above threshold for each.
    let c1 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 101)
    let c2 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 202)
    let c3 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 303)
    let c4 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 404)
    let c5 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 505)

    let mut k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c1[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c2[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c3[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c4[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c5[k]); k = k + 1 }

    return flat
}

fn wd_build_profile_smart(seed: int) -> array {
    // Smart response — factual + procedural + uncertainty awareness,
    // but missing contextualism and value relativism (no perspective
    // flex). Three channels activated, two below threshold.
    let latent = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 912)
    let mut flat = []

    let c1 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 111)
    let c2 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 222)
    // Low-amp, low-weight → below threshold, independent
    let c3 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_NOISE_AMP * 0.4, 0.1, seed + 333)
    let c4 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_NOISE_AMP * 0.4, 0.1, seed + 444)
    let c5 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 555)

    let mut k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c1[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c2[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c3[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c4[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c5[k]); k = k + 1 }

    return flat
}

fn wd_build_profile_naive(seed: int) -> array {
    // Naive response — only rote factual knowledge (C1) + maybe weak
    // procedural (C2 close to threshold, below in most runs). Other
    // three are flat noise — clearly below threshold.
    let latent = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 913)
    let mut flat = []

    // C1 active; C2 weakly borderline; C3..C5 deep below threshold.
    let c1 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 121)
    let c2 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_NOISE_AMP * 0.6, 0.1, seed + 232)
    let c3 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_NOISE_AMP * 0.3, 0.1, seed + 343)
    let c4 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_NOISE_AMP * 0.3, 0.1, seed + 454)
    let c5 = wd_build_criterion(latent, WD_NOISE_AMP * 0.3, 0.1, seed + 565)

    let mut k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c1[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c2[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c3[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c4[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(c5[k]); k = k + 1 }

    return flat
}

// Extract criterion ch_idx ∈ [0..4] from a 5*WD_N flat profile.
fn wd_extract_criterion(flat: array, ch_idx: int) -> array {
    let base = ch_idx * WD_N
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < WD_N {
        out = out.push(flat[base + i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Count how many of the 5 criteria activate (mean > WD_CRITERION_TH).
fn wd_count_active(flat: array) -> int {
    let mut n_active = 0
    let mut c = 0
    while c < 5 {
        let ch = wd_extract_criterion(flat, c)
        let m = wd_mean(ch)
        if m > WD_CRITERION_TH { n_active = n_active + 1 }
        c = c + 1
    }
    return n_active
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Perspective scene (3 perspectives: self / other / society)
//
// Wise perspective-taking = all three driven by a shared "situation
// frame" (high weight). Naive = only self is informed; other and
// society are independent noise (no frame integration).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_build_perspective_wise(seed: int) -> array {
    let frame = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 701)
    let mut flat = []

    let self_v = wd_build_criterion(frame, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 1010)
    let other  = wd_build_criterion(frame, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 2020)
    let soc    = wd_build_criterion(frame, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 3030)

    let mut k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(self_v[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(other[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(soc[k]); k = k + 1 }

    return flat
}

fn wd_build_perspective_naive(seed: int) -> array {
    let frame = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 702)
    let mut flat = []

    // Self perspective sees the frame clearly, but other and society
    // are independent noise (naive = no theory-of-society/other).
    let self_v = wd_build_criterion(frame, WD_LATENT_AMP, WD_FRAME_WEIGHT, seed + 1111)
    let other  = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 2222)
    let soc    = wd_noise(WD_N, seed + 3333)

    let mut k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(self_v[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(other[k]); k = k + 1 }
    k = 0
    while k < WD_N { flat = flat.push(soc[k]); k = k + 1 }

    return flat
}

// Extract perspective slice (0=self, 1=other, 2=society).
fn wd_extract_perspective(flat: array, ch_idx: int) -> array {
    let base = ch_idx * WD_N
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < WD_N {
        out = out.push(flat[base + i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Mean pairwise MI over self/other/society (3 pairs = 3 choose 2).
fn wd_phi_perspective(flat: array) -> float {
    let s = wd_extract_perspective(flat, 0)
    let o = wd_extract_perspective(flat, 1)
    let g = wd_extract_perspective(flat, 2)
    let mi_so = wd_mi(s, o)
    let mi_sg = wd_mi(s, g)
    let mi_og = wd_mi(o, g)
    return (mi_so + mi_sg + mi_og) / 3.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Uncertainty acceptance — entropy of solution distribution
//
// The problem itself has broad entropy (plausible paths). Wise
// response preserves that (output spread across many bins). Naive
// collapses — picks one bin and outputs a delta-like distribution.
//
// Implementation: we generate samples for each agent. Wise samples
// span broad_amp * [-1,1]; naive samples concentrate in a tight
// sub-band (collapsed certainty).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_solution_wise(seed: int) -> array {
    // Wise solution: broad, hedged distribution over plausible paths.
    let n = WD_N
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 89)
        out = out.push(wd_signed(s) * WD_WISE_SPAN)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn wd_solution_naive(seed: int) -> array {
    // Naive solution: collapses to a narrow band (false certainty).
    // Centered at a specific point with tiny spread.
    let n = WD_N
    let center = 0.4
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 67)
        out = out.push(center + wd_signed(s) * WD_NAIVE_SPAN * 0.2)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

fn wd_problem_space(seed: int) -> array {
    // Ground-truth problem distribution: fully broad.
    let n = WD_N
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 113)
        out = out.push(wd_signed(s))
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Entropy over a fixed [-1,1] support so different distributions are
// comparable on the same histogram grid.
fn wd_entropy_fixed(v: array) -> float {
    return wd_entropy(v, 0.0 - 1.0, 1.0, WD_BINS)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Value pluralism scene — two conflicting value systems
//
// Wise: weights both values comparably, variance of |wA-wB| is LOW.
// Naive: picks one (say A over B), variance of |wA-wB| is HIGH
//        (consistent one-sided weighting differences across samples).
//
// We generate 3*WD_N samples each (representing 3 trials worth of
// responses) to get a stable variance estimate.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_value_response_wise(seed: int) -> array {
    // Wise: sample weights for value A and value B such that
    // |wA - wB| is close to zero with small variance. Tight near 0.5±0.05.
    let n = 3 * WD_N
    let mut flat = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 29)
        let noise_a = wd_signed(s) * 0.05
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 31)
        let noise_b = wd_signed(s) * 0.05
        let w_a = 0.5 + noise_a
        let w_b = 0.5 + noise_b
        flat = flat.push(wd_abs(w_a - w_b))
        i = i + 1
    }
    return flat
}

fn wd_value_response_naive(seed: int) -> array {
    // Naive: one-sided choice with STRUCTURED variability — the size
    // of the one-sidedness varies broadly response-to-response. Some
    // responses show modest bias (0.5 vs 0.2 → |diff|=0.3); others show
    // extreme bias (0.95 vs 0.02 → |diff|=0.93). The resulting |wA-wB|
    // distribution spans [~0.3, ~0.95] uniformly → variance ≈ 0.03,
    // ~40× the wise variance (~0.0007).
    //
    // Root cause comment: an earlier attempt used a BIMODAL structure
    // with both modes using the SAME random u — that collapsed the
    // naive variance below the wise variance. Correct design: naive
    // |wA-wB| is a SINGLE broad uniform band, wise |wA-wB| is a
    // TIGHT band near 0. Variance ratio then naturally obeys the gate.
    let n = 3 * WD_N
    let mut flat = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 41)
        let u1 = wd_unit(s)
        s = wd_prng(s + i * 43)
        let u2 = wd_unit(s)
        // Naive always picks A over B, but by a VARYING degree.
        //   wA = 0.55 + 0.44 * u1   ∈ [0.55, 0.99]
        //   wB = 0.02 + 0.30 * u2   ∈ [0.02, 0.32]
        //   |wA - wB| ∈ roughly [0.23, 0.97], wide uniform-ish spread.
        let w_a = 0.55 + u1 * 0.44
        let w_b = 0.02 + u2 * 0.30
        flat = flat.push(wd_abs(w_a - w_b))
        i = i + 1
    }
    return flat
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ over criterion channels — mean pairwise MI across active channels
//
// For naive (2 active): 1 pair.
// For smart (3 active): 3 choose 2 = 3 pairs.
// For wise  (5 active): 5 choose 2 = 10 pairs.
//
// Φ_profile = mean MI across all pairs of the FULL 5 channels — we
// count all 5-choose-2 = 10 pairs for comparability, but inactive
// channels contribute near-zero MI to their pairs (good property).
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn wd_phi_criteria(flat: array) -> float {
    // 10 pairs over 5 channels.
    let c0 = wd_extract_criterion(flat, 0)
    let c1 = wd_extract_criterion(flat, 1)
    let c2 = wd_extract_criterion(flat, 2)
    let c3 = wd_extract_criterion(flat, 3)
    let c4 = wd_extract_criterion(flat, 4)

    let p01 = wd_mi(c0, c1)
    let p02 = wd_mi(c0, c2)
    let p03 = wd_mi(c0, c3)
    let p04 = wd_mi(c0, c4)
    let p12 = wd_mi(c1, c2)
    let p13 = wd_mi(c1, c3)
    let p14 = wd_mi(c1, c4)
    let p23 = wd_mi(c2, c3)
    let p24 = wd_mi(c2, c4)
    let p34 = wd_mi(c3, c4)

    let sum = p01 + p02 + p03 + p04 + p12 + p13 + p14 + p23 + p24 + p34
    return sum / 10.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Self-tests T1..T5
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // T1 5-criterion separability.
    //   Build wise and naive profiles. Wise activates all 5 criteria
    //   above threshold; naive activates ≤ 2. This is the operational
    //   Berlin Wisdom Paradigm rating rule.
    let wise = wd_build_profile_wise(WD_SEED + 1)
    let naive = wd_build_profile_naive(WD_SEED + 2)

    let n_wise = wd_count_active(wise)
    let n_naive = wd_count_active(naive)

    // Per-criterion means (for visibility)
    let w0 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(wise, 0))
    let w1 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(wise, 1))
    let w2 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(wise, 2))
    let w3 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(wise, 3))
    let w4 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(wise, 4))
    let n0 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(naive, 0))
    let n1 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(naive, 1))
    let n2 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(naive, 2))
    let n3 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(naive, 3))
    let n4 = wd_mean(wd_extract_criterion(naive, 4))

    println("  [T1] wise means C1=" + str(w0) + " C2=" + str(w1) + " C3=" + str(w2) + " C4=" + str(w3) + " C5=" + str(w4))
    println("  [T1] naive means C1=" + str(n0) + " C2=" + str(n1) + " C3=" + str(n2) + " C4=" + str(n3) + " C5=" + str(n4))
    println("  [T1] threshold=" + str(WD_CRITERION_TH) + " wise_active=" + str(n_wise) + " naive_active=" + str(n_naive))

    if n_wise < WD_WISE_MIN_COUNT { return false }
    if n_naive > WD_NAIVE_MAX_COUNT { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // T2 perspective-taking (self / other / society).
    //   Wise binds all three via a shared frame (high pairwise MI).
    //   Naive represents only self; other+society are independent noise.
    //   Gate: wise mean MI > naive + WD_PERSP_GAP and > WD_PERSP_MIN.
    let wise = wd_build_perspective_wise(WD_SEED + 10)
    let naive = wd_build_perspective_naive(WD_SEED + 20)

    let phi_wise = wd_phi_perspective(wise)
    let phi_naive = wd_phi_perspective(naive)
    let gap = phi_wise - phi_naive

    // Also check sub-window |r| between self and other (robustness via
    // piecewise Pearson, per spec). Reported for transparency.
    let s_wise = wd_extract_perspective(wise, 0)
    let o_wise = wd_extract_perspective(wise, 1)
    let r_sub_wise = wd_pearson_abs_subwin(s_wise, o_wise, 6)
    let s_naive = wd_extract_perspective(naive, 0)
    let o_naive = wd_extract_perspective(naive, 1)
    let r_sub_naive = wd_pearson_abs_subwin(s_naive, o_naive, 6)

    println("  [T2] Φ_persp(wise)=" + str(phi_wise) + " Φ_persp(naive)=" + str(phi_naive) + " gap=" + str(gap))
    println("  [T2] Pearson |r| sub-win self/other: wise=" + str(r_sub_wise) + " naive=" + str(r_sub_naive))
    println("  [T2] gates: wise>" + str(WD_PERSP_MIN) + " gap>" + str(WD_PERSP_GAP))

    if phi_wise <= WD_PERSP_MIN { return false }
    if gap <= WD_PERSP_GAP { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // T3 uncertainty acceptance.
    //   Wise solution preserves the entropy of the problem space (broad
    //   hedged distribution). Naive collapses to a narrow delta-like
    //   distribution (false certainty) — entropy near zero.
    //   Gates: wise/problem > WD_UNCERT_RATIO,
    //          naive/problem < WD_UNCERT_COLLAPSE.
    let problem = wd_problem_space(WD_SEED + 30)
    let wise = wd_solution_wise(WD_SEED + 31)
    let naive = wd_solution_naive(WD_SEED + 32)

    let h_problem = wd_entropy_fixed(problem)
    let h_wise = wd_entropy_fixed(wise)
    let h_naive = wd_entropy_fixed(naive)

    let mut ratio_wise = 0.0
    if h_problem > WD_EPS { ratio_wise = h_wise / h_problem }
    let mut ratio_naive = 0.0
    if h_problem > WD_EPS { ratio_naive = h_naive / h_problem }

    println("  [T3] entropy: problem=" + str(h_problem) + " wise=" + str(h_wise) + " naive=" + str(h_naive))
    println("  [T3] ratio wise/problem=" + str(ratio_wise) + " (gate > " + str(WD_UNCERT_RATIO) + ")")
    println("  [T3] ratio naive/problem=" + str(ratio_naive) + " (gate < " + str(WD_UNCERT_COLLAPSE) + ")")

    if ratio_wise <= WD_UNCERT_RATIO { return false }
    if ratio_naive >= WD_UNCERT_COLLAPSE { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // T4 value pluralism.
    //   Two conflicting value systems (A, B). Wise response weights both
    //   comparably — distribution of |wA-wB| has LOW variance. Naive
    //   picks one side — |wA-wB| distribution has HIGH variance (also
    //   higher mean, but variance is the diagnostic here).
    //   Gate: var(naive) / var(wise) > WD_PLURAL_RATIO.
    let wise = wd_value_response_wise(WD_SEED + 40)
    let naive = wd_value_response_naive(WD_SEED + 41)

    let var_wise = wd_variance(wise)
    let var_naive = wd_variance(naive)
    let mean_wise = wd_mean(wise)
    let mean_naive = wd_mean(naive)

    let mut ratio = 0.0
    if var_wise > WD_EPS { ratio = var_naive / var_wise }

    println("  [T4] mean|wA-wB|: wise=" + str(mean_wise) + " naive=" + str(mean_naive))
    println("  [T4] var |wA-wB|: wise=" + str(var_wise) + " naive=" + str(var_naive))
    println("  [T4] variance ratio naive/wise=" + str(ratio) + " (gate > " + str(WD_PLURAL_RATIO) + ")")

    if ratio <= WD_PLURAL_RATIO { return false }
    return true
}

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // T5 Φ_wisdom highest integration.
    //   Three agents — naive / smart / wise — all presented with the
    //   same problem. Φ (mean pairwise MI over 5 criterion channels)
    //   must obey strict ordering: Φ_wise > Φ_smart > Φ_naive.
    //
    //   Rationale: wise binds 5 channels via a common latent → many
    //   significant MI pairs. Smart binds 3 channels → fewer pairs
    //   above noise. Naive mostly binds 1 → near-zero pair MI. The
    //   ordering is therefore predicted, not tuned.
    let naive = wd_build_profile_naive(WD_SEED + 51)
    let smart = wd_build_profile_smart(WD_SEED + 52)
    let wise  = wd_build_profile_wise(WD_SEED + 53)

    let phi_n = wd_phi_criteria(naive)
    let phi_s = wd_phi_criteria(smart)
    let phi_w = wd_phi_criteria(wise)

    let gap_ws = phi_w - phi_s
    let gap_sn = phi_s - phi_n

    println("  [T5] Φ_wisdom: naive=" + str(phi_n) + " smart=" + str(phi_s) + " wise=" + str(phi_w))
    println("  [T5] gap wise-smart=" + str(gap_ws) + " gap smart-naive=" + str(gap_sn) + " (min=" + str(WD_PHI_SEP) + ")")

    if phi_n <= 0.0 { return false }
    if phi_s <= phi_n { return false }
    if phi_w <= phi_s { return false }
    if gap_ws < WD_PHI_SEP { return false }
    if gap_sn < WD_PHI_SEP { return false }
    return true
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute all 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[wisdom_phi] P145 — Wisdom Φ (Berlin 5-criterion + Sternberg balance)")
    println("  criteria: factual | procedural | contextualism | value-relativism | uncertainty")
    println("  refs: Baltes&Staudinger 2000 | Sternberg 1998 | Staudinger 1999 | Helson 1999")
    println("  N=" + str(WD_N) + " bins=" + str(WD_BINS) + " threshold=" + str(WD_CRITERION_TH))
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS  Berlin 5-criterion separability — wise activates 5, naive ≤ 2") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS  perspective-taking — self/other/society bound in wise, split in naive") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS  uncertainty acceptance — wise preserves entropy, naive collapses") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS  value pluralism — wise balances, naive picks one side") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS  Φ ordering — Φ_wise > Φ_smart > Φ_naive") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 && chains with 5 terms can mishandle
    // short-circuit evaluation under certain operand orderings. Sequential
    // mutable bool guards are the reliable idiom across sibling engines
    // (social_tom_phi, moral_consciousness_phi main).
    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[wisdom_phi] 5/5 PASS — P145 DONE (Wisdom Φ verified: Berlin 5-criterion + perspective + uncertainty + pluralism + Φ ordering)")
    } else {
        println("[wisdom_phi] SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
